<h2>What to Look for When Choosing a Septic Pumping Company</h2>

<p>Five things matter more than star ratings:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Flat-rate phone quotes.</strong> A company that won't quote on the phone is leaving themselves room to upsell on-site. Reputable Iowa pumpers can quote within $25 once they know your tank size and access.</li>
  <li><strong>Iowa DNR septage hauler licensing.</strong> Required for legal pumping and disposal. Any legitimate pumper carries this and can confirm on request.</li>
  <li><strong>Time of Transfer certification.</strong> If you might sell within the next 5 years, prioritize pumpers who can also handle your eventual Iowa Time of Transfer inspection. See our guide to the <a href="/blog/iowa-time-of-transfer-septic-inspection/">Iowa Time of Transfer septic inspection</a> for context.</li>
  <li><strong>Written invoices with tank condition notes.</strong> The invoice should show gallons pumped, baffle condition, and any flagged issues, not just a single line item. See <a href="/blog/what-to-expect-septic-pumping-appointment/">what to expect during a septic pumping appointment</a> for the full invoice checklist.</li>
  <li><strong>24/7 emergency dispatch.</strong> Septic emergencies don't wait. A pumper with a real 24/7 line is the difference between a $475 service call and overnight raw sewage in the basement.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>

<p>The Des Moines metro has more credible septic pumping options than most Iowa cities, which is good news for homeowners. Get two phone quotes for any non-emergency job, ask each pumper to walk through what's included, and pick the one whose answers are most specific. Vague answers up front almost always mean surprises on the invoice.</p>

